# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: clipboard-api
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:clipboard-api/api-clipboard] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:clipboard-api/api-clipboard] It’s been available across browsers since March 2020.
[src:clipboard-api/api-clipboard] The **`Clipboard`** interface of the Clipboard API provides read and write access to the contents of the system clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/api-clipboard] This allows a web application to implement cut, copy, and paste features.
[src:clipboard-api/api-clipboard] The system clipboard is exposed through the global `Navigator.clipboard` property.
[src:clipboard-api/api-clipboard] All of the Clipboard API methods operate asynchronously; they return a `Promise` which is resolved once the clipboard access has been completed.
[src:clipboard-api/api-clipboard] The promise is rejected if clipboard access is denied.
[src:clipboard-api/api-clipboard] All the methods require a secure context.
[src:clipboard-api/api-clipboard] Additional requirements for using the API are discussed in the Security consideration section of the API overview topic.
[src:clipboard-api/api-clipboard] Requests arbitrary data (such as images) from the clipboard, returning a `Promise` that resolves with an array of `ClipboardItem` objects containing the clipboard's contents.
[src:clipboard-api/api-clipboard] Requests text from the system clipboard, returning a `Promise` that is fulfilled with a string containing the clipboard's text once it's available.
[src:clipboard-api/api-clipboard] Writes arbitrary data to the system clipboard, returning a `Promise` that resolves when the operation completes.
[src:clipboard-api/api-clipboard] Writes text to the system clipboard, returning a `Promise` that is resolved once the text is fully copied into the clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/api-clipboard] Fired when the system clipboard contents are changed in any way, for example via a system copy command, or via an API method such as `Clipboard.writeText()`.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] The **Clipboard API** provides the ability to respond to clipboard commands (cut, copy, and paste), as well as to asynchronously read from and write to the system clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] The *system clipboard* is a data buffer belonging to the operating system hosting the browser, which is used for short-term data storage and/or data transfers between documents or applications.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] It is usually implemented as an anonymous, temporary data buffer, sometimes called the *paste buffer*, that can be accessed from most or all programs within the environment via defined programming interfaces.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] The Clipboard API allows users to programmatically read and write text and other kinds of data to and from the system clipboard in secure contexts, provided the user has met the criteria outlined in the Security considerations.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] Events are fired as the result of `cut`, `copy`, and `paste` operations modifying the clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] The events have a default action, for example the `copy` action copies the current selection to the system clipboard by default.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] The default action can be overridden by the event handler — see each of the events for more information.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] There is also a `clipboardchange` event fired directly on the `Clipboard` object whenever the system clipboard's contents are changed.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] This is useful for notifying apps of a change to the system clipboard, for example if they have their own clipboard that needs to be kept in sync.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] Provides an interface for reading and writing text and data to or from the system clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] The specification refers to this as the 'Async Clipboard API'.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] Represents events fired whenever the contents of the system clipboard are changed.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] Represents events providing information related to modification of the clipboard, that is `cut`, `copy`, and `paste` events.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] The specification refers to this as the 'Clipboard Event API'.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] Represents a single item format, used when reading or writing data.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] The Clipboard API extends the following APIs, adding the listed features.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] Returns a `Clipboard` object that provides read and write access to the system clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] An event fired whenever the user initiates a copy action.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] An event fired whenever the user initiates a cut action.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] An event fired whenever the user initiates a paste action.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] The Clipboard API allows users to programmatically read and write text and other kinds of data to and from the system clipboard in secure contexts.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] When reading from the clipboard, the specification requires that a user has recently interacted with the page (transient user activation) and that the call is made as a result of the user interacting with a browser or OS "paste element" (such as choosing "Paste" on a native context menu).
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] In practice, browsers often allow read operations that do not satisfy these requirements, while placing other requirements instead (such as a permission or per-operation prompt).
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] For writing to the clipboard the specification expects that the page has been granted the Permissions API `clipboard-write` permission, and the browser may also require transient user activation.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] Browsers may place additional restrictions over use of the methods to access the clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] The `clipboardchange` event is only fired with sticky activation or after the `clipboard-read` permission is granted.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] Browser implementations have diverged from the specification.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] The system clipboard is accessed through the `Navigator.clipboard` global.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] This snippet fetches the text from the clipboard and appends it to the first element found with the class `editor`.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-api] Since `readText()` returns an empty string if the clipboard isn't text, this code is safe.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The **clipboard** is a buffer that some operating systems provide for short-term storage and transfer across applications.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The clipboard provides an application programming interface by which programs can specify cut, copy and paste operations.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] It is left to the program to define methods for the user to command these operations, which may include keybindings and menu selections.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] When an element is copied or cut, the clipboard must store enough information to enable a sensible result no matter where the element is pasted.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Application programs may extend the clipboard functions that the operating system provides.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] A clipboard manager may give the user additional control over the clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Specific clipboard semantics vary among operating systems, can also vary between versions of the same system, and can sometimes be changed by programs and by user preferences.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Windows and macOS support a single clipboard transaction; however, Linux desktops generally provide a full history of clipboard transactions (sometimes called a kill ring) to the user, allowing them to store several pieces of information at once before retrieving them on demand.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Clipboards as buffers for small text snippets were first used by Pentti Kanerva when he used it to store deleted pieces of text in order to restore them.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Since one could delete text in one place and restore it in another, the term "delete" wasn't what one would expect in this case.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Larry Tesler renamed this in 1973 as cut, copy, and paste and coined the term "clipboard" for this buffer, since these techniques need a clipboard for temporary saving the copied or cut data.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Applications communicate through the clipboard by providing either serialized representations of an object, or a promise (for larger objects).
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The sending and receiving application negotiate the formats which can be transferred in between them, oftentimes with the active GUI widget responsible for providing acceptable type transformations.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The pasteboard allows for transfer of common items such as URLs, colors, images, strings, attributed strings (Rich text), and sounds.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The operating system and GUI toolkit may provide some common conversions, for example converting from rich text to plain text and vice versa.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Various type identifiers for data transfer are supported by modern operating systems, which may automatically provide acceptable mappings between type systems, such as between MIME and Uniform Type Identifier.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Clipboard hijacking or clipboard injection is an exploit in which a person's clipboard's content is replaced by malicious data, such as a link to a malicious web site.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] For example, if a user copies a cryptocurrency receiving address into the clipboard, a hijacking program can overwrite it with an address controlled by the hijacker, so that when the user pastes the address their cryptocurrency is transmitted to the hijacker instead of the intended recipient.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] While some security-holes were patched, JavaScript can still be used to modify clipboard content via an attack dubbed 'pastejacking'.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Dylan Ayrey who developed the attack set up a website that demonstrates how this exploit can be used to trick a user into running commands they didn't want to run.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] There have been exploits where web pages grab clipboard data.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] In early 2013 researchers exposed risks stemming from Android-based password managers and documented how passwords in 21 of the most popular of these apps could be accessed by any other app on an Android device including those with extremely low-level privileges.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Joe Siegrist notes that this is an "OS-level issue that impacts everything running on Android".
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Clipboard manager extensions add functionality to the integrated clipboard functions of an operating system.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] They are applications that enable the user to manipulate the clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] On platforms such as Linux that use multiple incompatible GUI toolkits, clipboard managers are often used to transfer data between applications using different such frameworks.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] When a clipboard manager provides multiple cut and paste transactions, the clipboard is treated as a stack or scrap book, with new cuts and copies being placed on a list of recent transactions.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The standard paste operation copies the most recent transaction, while specialized pastes provide access to the other stored transactions.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] These managers generally also provide a window that displays the transaction history and allows the user to select earlier copies, edit them, change their format and even search amongst them.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Windows, macOS, Linux, X11, Android, iOS) do not save the clipboard contents to any persistent storage – when a user logs out or reboots the system the clipboard contents are deleted – an added functionality is to save the clipboard persistently.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Another example is making the local clipboard work with online applications by saving the clipboard data to the online location upon a copy or cut event, making this data available to online applications for pasting.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Clipboard managers can also serve as tools to overcome the limitation of software not supporting copying and pasting (for example, while logging into remote Windows server, one cannot copy and paste their user name and password).
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The Amiga operating system uses 256 units, so one has multiple clipboards at the same time.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Android provides a clipboard that can hold up to one clip object and is accessible system-wide.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Simple text is stored directly in the clipboard; complex data are stored by reference.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The clip object has one of three formats: text string, URI object, or intent.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] To interact with the clipboard, an app uses the class ClipboardManager and system calls to cut, copy, and paste objects.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] In Android 8.0, the clipboard first appears in the user interface: In a situation where the user prepares to paste from the clipboard, a "Clipboard" option appears that gives the user access to many objects copied or cut to the clipboard in the past.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Apart from that, and in earlier versions, the user has no access to the clipboard except in apps that make it available to the user.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The clipboard is called "pasteboard" in iOS similar to OS X.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Apps on this operating system can create additional pasteboards, called instances of the UIPasteboard class, which can be public or private.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] One instance can hold a single item or multiple items in different formats.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The formats are identified by Uniform Type Identifiers (UTI).
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The clipboard in macOS holds one item in multiple available formats.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The contents of the clipboard can be viewed by selecting the Show Clipboard menu item from the Finder's Edit menu.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The raw data and the stored formats can be seen using the ClipboardViewer.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The clipboard in Microsoft Windows and ReactOS holds one item in multiple available formats.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Every item has at least one clipboard format, but can have different types of format of the same data.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Up to and including Windows XP the clipboard could be accessed via the ClipBook Viewer application.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] In newer versions of Windows the content can be accessed via clipboard managers.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Windows 10 and Windows 11 include the Clipboard application, allowing for the storage of multiple text-based clipboard items.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] It can be accessed by pressing Windows+V.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Symbian S60 (Series 60), depending on edition, has a built-in clipboard with image and richtext storing support.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] In S60v3 (S60 3rd Edition, Symbian 9.1–9.2) examples of clipboard provided with the SDK: `..\Examples\SysLibs\Clipboard\Basics`.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] In Symbian Belle, clipboard support defined with `CClipboard` Class in the Basic Application Framework Library (BAFL).
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] There was a number of free and commercial third party clipboard managing applications with multi-item clipboard support created for different Symbian editions.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The X Window System commonly used on Unix and Linux systems provides three clipboards, which are named "CLIPBOARD", "PRIMARY" and "SECONDARY".
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The usage and handling of various selections is not standardized.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Most modern toolkits and desktop environments, including GNOME or KDE, follow a widely accepted convention, outlined in the freedesktop.org specification.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] One selection, CLIPBOARD, is used for traditional clipboard semantics, with shortcuts identical to Windows.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Another selection, PRIMARY, is an X11-specific mechanism.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Data is "copied" immediately upon highlighting and pasted with the third (middle) mouse button.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] This copied data is usually separated from the CLIPBOARD selection and does not change its contents.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] SECONDARY was planned as an alternative to PRIMARY but is only used inconsistently.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Command line access to the three clipboards is available with tools xclip and xsel.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The main difference to OS X and Windows is that no data is actually stored in the CLIPBOARD-clipboard but only the reference to the copied or cut data.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The application claims the ownership of the CLIPBOARD selection and communicates its ownership to the X Server.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] When pasting this data, the data and its available formats are requested from the application that owns the CLIPBOARD selection.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] Applications can access the clipboard or its data via APIs.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] In Qt a wrapper for every supported platform exists.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] It provides access to window system clipboards with the use of the class QClipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] This class facilitates access to common data types by functions.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-computing] The data type of the element stored in the clipboard is indicated via MIME and MIME data can also be put in the clipboard with help of functions from this class.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-writetext] The **`writeText()`** method of the `Clipboard` interface writes the specified text to the system clipboard, returning a `Promise` that is resolved once the system clipboard has been updated.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-writetext] The string to be written to the clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-writetext] A `Promise` that is resolved once the clipboard's contents have been updated.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-writetext] Thrown if writing to the clipboard is not allowed.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-writetext] Writing to the clipboard can only be done in a secure context.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-writetext] Additional security requirements are covered in the Security consideration section of the API overview topic.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboard-writetext] This example sets the clipboard's contents to the string "<empty clipboard>".
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] Since June 2024, this feature works across the latest devices and browser versions.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] This feature might not work in older devices or browsers.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] The **`ClipboardItem`** interface of the Clipboard API represents a single item format, used when reading or writing clipboard data using `Clipboard.read()` and `Clipboard.write()` respectively.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] The **`ClipboardItem`** interface enables developers to use a single type to represent a range of different data formats.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] Creates a new **`ClipboardItem`** object, with the MIME type as the key and the data as the value.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] Returns an `Array` of MIME types available within the **`ClipboardItem`**.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] Returns one of the following: `"unspecified"`, `"inline"` or `"attachment"`.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] Checks whether a given MIME type is supported by the clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] This enables a website to detect whether a MIME type is supported before attempting to write data.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with a `Blob` of the requested MIME type, or an error if the MIME type is not found.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] In this example we first define two constants containing references to a `<p>` element containing some text and a `<button>` element.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] Next, we define a function called `copyToClipboard()`.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] This starts off by storing a `"text/plain"` MIME type in a constant, then creating an object called `clipboardItemData` that contains one property with a key equal to the MIME type and a value of the text we want to copy to the clipboard (the content of the `<p>` element, in this case).
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] Because we are working with text, we can pass it in directly rather than having to create a `Blob`.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] We construct a new `ClipboardItem` object using the `ClipboardItem()` constructor, and pass it into the `Clipboard.write()` method to copy the text to the clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] Finally, we add an event listener to the `<button>` so that it runs the function when pressed.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] Here we use `supports()` to check whether the `image/svg+xml` MIME data type is supported.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] If it is, we fetch an SVG image with the Fetch API, and then read it into a `Blob`, which we can use to create a `ClipboardItem` that is written to the clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] Here we're returning all items on the clipboard via the `clipboard.read()` method.
[src:clipboard-api/clipboarditem] Then utilizing the `ClipboardItem.types` property to set the `getType()` argument and return the corresponding blob object.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The command names are a (skeuomorphic) interface metaphor based on the physical procedure used in manuscript print editing to create a page layout, like with paper.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The commands were pioneered into computing by Xerox PARC in 1974, popularized by Apple Computer in the 1983 Lisa workstation and the 1984 Macintosh computer, and in a few home computer applications such as the 1984 word processor Cut & Paste.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] This interaction technique has close associations with related techniques in graphical user interfaces (GUIs) that use pointing devices such as a computer mouse (by drag and drop, for example).
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Typically, clipboard support is provided by an operating system as part of its GUI and widget toolkit.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The capability to replicate information with ease, changing it between contexts and applications, involves privacy concerns because of the risks of disclosure when handling sensitive information.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Terms like *cloning*, *copy forward*, *carry forward*, or *re-use* refer to the dissemination of such information through documents, and may be subject to regulation by administrative bodies.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The term "cut and paste" comes from the traditional practice in manuscript editing, whereby people cut paragraphs from a page with scissors and paste them onto another page.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] This practice remained standard into the 1980s.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Stationery stores sold "editing scissors" with blades long enough to cut an 8½"-wide page.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The advent of photocopiers made the practice easier and more flexible.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The act of copying or transferring text from one part of a computer-based document ("buffer") to a different location within the same or different computer-based document was a part of the earliest on-line computer editors.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] As soon as computer data entry moved from punch-cards to online files (in the mid/late 1960s) there were "commands" for accomplishing this operation.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] This mechanism was often used to transfer frequently-used commands or text snippets from additional buffers into the document, as was the case with the QED text editor.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The earliest editors (designed for teleprinter terminals) provided keyboard commands to delineate a contiguous region of text, then delete or move it.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Since moving a region of text requires first removing it from its initial location and then inserting it into its new location, various schemes had to be invented to allow for this multi-step process to be specified by the user.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Often this was done with a "move" command, but some text editors required that the text be first put into some temporary location for later retrieval/placement.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] In 1983, the Apple Lisa became the first text editing system to call that temporary location "the clipboard".
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Earlier control schemes such as NLS used a verb—object command structure, where the command name was provided first and the object to be copied or moved was second.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The inversion from verb—object to object—verb on which copy and paste are based, where the user selects the object to be operated before initiating the operation, was an innovation crucial for the success of the desktop metaphor as it allowed copy and move operations based on direct manipulation.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Inspired by early line and character editors, such as Pentti Kanerva's TV-Edit, that broke a move or copy operation into two steps—between which the user could invoke a preparatory action such as navigation—Lawrence G.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] "Larry" Tesler proposed the names "cut" and "copy" for the first step and "paste" for the second step.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Beginning in 1974, he and colleagues at Xerox PARC implemented several text editors that used cut/copy-and-paste commands to move and copy text.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Apple Computer popularized this paradigm with its Lisa (1983) and Macintosh (1984) operating systems and applications.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The functions were mapped to key combinations using the ⌘ Command key as a special modifier, which is held down while also pressing X for cut, C for copy, or V for paste.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] These few keyboard shortcuts allow the user to perform all the basic editing operations, and the keys are clustered at the left end of the bottom row of the standard QWERTY keyboard.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The IBM Common User Access (CUA) standard also uses combinations of the Insert, Del, Shift and Control keys.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Early versions of Windows used the IBM standard.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Microsoft later also adopted the Apple key combinations with the introduction of Windows, using the control key as modifier key.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Similar patterns of key combinations, later borrowed by others, are widely available in most GUI applications.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The original cut, copy, and paste workflow, as implemented at PARC, utilizes a unique workflow: With two windows on the same screen, the user could use the mouse to pick a point at which to make an insertion in one window (or a segment of text to replace).
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Then, by holding shift and selecting the copy source elsewhere on the same screen, the copy would be made as soon as the shift was released.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Similarly, holding shift and control would copy and cut (delete) the source.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] This workflow requires many fewer keystrokes/mouse clicks than the current multi-step workflows, and did not require an explicit copy buffer.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] It was dropped, one presumes, because the original Apple and IBM GUIs were not high enough density to permit multiple windows, as were the PARC machines, and so multiple simultaneous windows were rarely used.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Computer-based editing can involve very frequent use of cut-and-paste operations.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Most software-suppliers provide several methods for performing such tasks, and this can involve (for example) key combinations, pulldown menus, pop-up menus, or toolbar buttons.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The user performs a "cut" operation via key combination Ctrl+x (⌘+x for Macintosh users), menu, or other means.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Visibly, "cut" text immediately disappears from its location.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] "Cut" files typically change color to indicate that they will be moved.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Conceptually, the text has now moved to a location often called the clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The clipboard typically remains invisible.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] On most systems only one clipboard location exists, hence another cut or copy operation overwrites the previously stored information.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Many UNIX text-editors provide multiple clipboard entries, as do some Macintosh programs such as Clipboard Master, and Windows clipboard-manager programs such as the one in Microsoft Office.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The user selects a location for insertion by some method, typically by clicking at the desired insertion point.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] A *paste* operation takes place which visibly inserts the clipboard text at the insertion point.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] (The paste operation does not typically destroy the clipboard text: it remains available in the clipboard and the user can insert additional copies at other points).
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Whereas cut-and-paste often takes place with a mouse-equivalent in Windows-like GUI environments, it may also occur entirely from the keyboard, especially in UNIX text editors, such as Pico or vi.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Cutting and pasting without a mouse can involve a selection (for which Ctrl+x is pressed in most graphical systems) or the entire current line, but it may also involve text after the cursor until the end of the line and other more sophisticated operations.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The clipboard usually stays invisible, because the operations of cutting and pasting, while actually independent, usually take place in quick succession, and the user (usually) needs no assistance in understanding the operation or maintaining mental context.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Some application programs provide a means of viewing, or sometimes even editing, the data on the clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The term "copy-and-paste" refers to the popular, simple method of reproducing text or other data from a source to a destination.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] It differs from cut and paste in that the original source text or data does not get deleted or removed.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] The popularity of this method stems from its simplicity and the ease with which users can move data between various applications visually – without resorting to permanent storage.
[src:clipboard-api/cut-copy-and-paste] Use in healthcare documentation and electronic health records are sensitive, with potential for the introduction of medical errors, information overload, and fraud.
[src:clipboard-api/navigator-clipboard] The **`clipboard`** read-only property of the `Navigator` interface returns a `Clipboard` object used to read and write the clipboard's contents.
[src:clipboard-api/navigator-clipboard] This is the entry point to the Clipboard API, which can be used to implement cut, copy, and paste features within a web application.
[src:clipboard-api/navigator-clipboard] The `Clipboard` object used to access the system clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/navigator-clipboard] The following code uses `navigator.clipboard` to access the system clipboard in order to read text contents from the clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/navigator-clipboard] This snippet replaces the contents of the element whose class is `"clip-text"` with the text contents of the clipboard.
[src:clipboard-api/navigator-clipboard] Perhaps this code is being used in a browser extension that displays the current clipboard contents, automatically updating periodically or when specific events fire.
[src:clipboard-api/navigator-clipboard] If the clipboard is empty or doesn't contain text, the `"clip-text"` element's contents are cleared.
[src:clipboard-api/navigator-clipboard] This happens because `readText()` returns an empty string if the clipboard is empty or doesn't contain text.
